in two seconds,

253
00:15:57,668 --> 00:15:58,795
and if he's
the least bit skittish,

254
00:15:58,878 --> 00:16:00,671
the chance will be lost.

255
00:16:06,886 --> 00:16:08,012
Hey, it's your station, Mike.
It's your call.

256
00:16:10,223 --> 00:16:12,225
You know what I would do.

257
00:16:20,108 --> 00:16:23,402
If we think she was
compromised in Russia...

258
00:16:23,486 --> 00:16:24,612
Why would we give her
the go-ahead

259
00:16:24,695 --> 00:16:26,781
to meet with a Russian?

260
00:16:26,864 --> 00:16:27,907
I think I just answered
my own question.

261
00:16:27,990 --> 00:16:30,785
To get her to incriminate
herself, right?

262
00:16:30,868 --> 00:16:32,954
Right, which is how come I was
pushing so hard for backup.

263
00:16:33,037 --> 00:16:36,249
We need eyes and ears
on her the whole time.

264
00:16:36,332 --> 00:16:38,960
- What about a bug?
- What about it?

265
00:16:39,043 --> 00:16:39,794
Any chance you could
slip one into her purse?

266
00:16:39,877 --> 00:16:42,421
- Carrie's purse?
- Yeah.

267
00:16:42,505 --> 00:16:44,799
Uh, highly unlikely.

268
00:16:44,882 --> 00:16:47,593
Not buying
the friendship routine, huh?

269
00:16:47,677 --> 00:16:50,638
No, she is, we're just not
braiding each other's hair yet.

270
00:16:50,721 --> 00:16:54,016
Parabolic it is, then.

271
00:16:54,100 --> 00:16:57,854
Tell her one team in a van
parked where no one can see.

272
00:18:29,445 --> 00:18:30,321
- <i>Hello?</i>
- Tasneem.

273
00:18:30,404 --> 00:18:33,074
- <i>Who's this?</i>
- It's Jalal.

274
00:18:33,157 --> 00:18:35,076
- <i>What the hell are you doing?</i>
- We have a problem.

275
00:18:35,159 --> 00:18:36,788
<i>You're on an open line.</i>

276
00:18:36,871 --> 00:18:39,082
<i>I told you never to call me
on an open line.</i>

277
00:18:39,165 --> 00:18:40,625
<i>Tasneem?
Tasneem?</i>

278
00:19:20,581 --> 00:19:21,374
Mind if I join?

279
00:19:21,457 --> 00:19:23,334
Not at all.

280
00:19:32,510 --> 00:19:35,054
You ever sleep?

281
00:19:36,764 --> 00:19:38,016
Is it that obvious?

282
00:19:40,268 --> 00:19:42,312
You're never in your room.

283
00:19:42,395 --> 00:19:44,022
I'm right next door.
Walls are like paper.

284
00:19:49,736 --> 00:19:52,989
So, uh, what happens tomorrow?

285
00:19:53,990 --> 00:19:57,535
Your guess is as good as mine.

286
00:19:57,618 --> 00:19:59,454
Let's say Yevgeny
asks to defect.

287
00:19:59,537 --> 00:20:01,456
What's the procedure?

288
00:20:01,539 --> 00:20:04,208
That he won't do.

289
00:20:04,292 --> 00:20:06,127
Why not?
I thought you said...

290
00:20:06,210 --> 00:20:10,256
I said he was a candidate
for recruitment, not defection.

291
00:20:10,340 --> 00:20:12,300
The last thing a field guy
like Yevgeny wants

292
00:20:12,383 --> 00:20:14,844
is a new identity
and a condo in Scottsdale.

293
00:20:14,927 --> 00:20:18,014
You know him better
than anybody, I guess.

294
00:20:20,308 --> 00:20:21,893
Is that what Mike told you?

295
00:20:21,976 --> 00:20:24,604
No, I just assumed.

296
00:20:24,687 --> 00:20:26,397
Don't assume.

297
00:20:31,152 --> 00:20:32,904
What has he told you?

298
00:20:32,987 --> 00:20:34,322
Not much.

299
00:20:36,783 --> 00:20:38,826
Come on.

300
00:20:40,953 --> 00:20:44,082
Your long stay in Russia
raised some flags.

301
00:20:48,586 --> 00:20:51,589
Are you spying on me, Jenna?

302
00:20:51,672 --> 00:20:54,258
Mike send you up here
to take my temperature?

303
00:20:56,135 --> 00:20:56,177
No.

304
00:21:11,275 --> 00:21:15,780
I've met Yevgeny Gromov
exactly five times in my life.

305
00:21:15,863 --> 00:21:17,907
Two of those times have
happened right here in Kabul

306
00:21:17,990 --> 00:21:19,909
over the past few days.

307
00:21:21,536 --> 00:21:24,789
For all I know...

308
00:21:24,872 --> 00:21:26,749
he's staging this whole event
just to throw more shade on me

309
00:21:26,833 --> 00:21:29,127
and do what he does best...

310
00:21:29,210 --> 00:21:31,212
spread rumor and innuendo,

311
00:21:31,295 --> 00:21:33,714
divide us against ourselves.

312
00:21:33,798 --> 00:21:36,092
Why even agree
to meet with him, then?

313
00:21:36,175 --> 00:21:39,637
'Cause I could be wrong.

314
00:21:39,720 --> 00:21:42,473
He could just as easily
be the genuine article.

315
00:21:45,685 --> 00:21:47,270
How you gonna know
which it is?

316
00:21:47,353 --> 00:21:49,105
That's the thing...
you never really do.

317
00:21:51,607 --> 00:21:53,568
Not 100%, anyway.

318
00:22:15,339 --> 00:22:18,926
You're free to go.
No one will stop you.

319
00:22:50,541 --> 00:22:52,001
Wait!

320
00:22:53,920 --> 00:22:55,213
Wait.

321
00:22:56,797 --> 00:22:58,799
What's happened?

322
00:23:21,072 --> 00:23:23,032
What is this place?

323
00:23:23,699 --> 00:23:25,243
<i>Badonbaay.</i>

324
00:23:28,079 --> 00:23:31,332
It means
"where the clouds end."

325
00:23:31,415 --> 00:23:33,459
My father used
to bring me here.

326
00:23:36,921 --> 00:23:40,132
There, that's where I grew up,

327
00:23:40,216 --> 00:23:42,426
at the end of the valley.

328
00:23:42,510 --> 00:23:44,262
Afghanistan.

329
00:23:48,516 --> 00:23:50,768
My unlucky country.

330
00:24:01,028 --> 00:24:03,739
It was Jalal who tried
to have me killed.

331
00:24:09,120 --> 00:24:11,038
He's the youngest
of my four sons,

332
00:24:11,122 --> 00:24:13,958
the only one
who's still alive.

333
00:24:14,041 --> 00:24:16,752
Yes, I know.

334
00:24:16,836 --> 00:24:18,754
I was hoping for something
more for him

335
00:24:18,838 --> 00:24:19,672
than war and death.

336
00:24:19,755 --> 00:24:22,967
It's not too late.

337
00:24:24,719 --> 00:24:27,013
Anybody else
would be dead already.

338
00:24:28,347 --> 00:24:29,890
Surely you can make
an exception

339
00:24:29,974 --> 00:24:31,350
for your own child.

340
00:24:31,434 --> 00:24:34,186
Not without compromising
my command.

341
00:24:36,564 --> 00:24:40,484
No, the only other option
is to step down.

342
00:24:40,568 --> 00:24:42,278
Don't do that.

343
00:24:44,822 --> 00:24:48,326
Maybe it's time.

344
00:24:48,409 --> 00:24:49,201
Some have said as much.

345
00:24:49,285 --> 00:24:51,120
There are many
who would take my place.

346
00:24:51,203 --> 00:24:53,664
None who have the power
or influence

347
00:24:53,748 --> 00:24:55,333
to end the war.

348
00:24:57,793 --> 00:25:00,171
You overstate my standing.

349
00:25:01,631 --> 00:25:04,216
Is that why they call you
"the Arrow of God"?

350
00:25:09,013 --> 00:25:11,474
I'm...

351
00:25:11,557 --> 00:25:12,808
just a man.

352
00:25:14,852 --> 00:25:18,147
Then you are a man
like Faisal was to the Saudis,

353
00:25:18,230 --> 00:25:20,650
Kemal to the Turks.

354
00:25:46,133 --> 00:25:46,884
<i>Where the fuck is he?</i>

355
00:25:46,967 --> 00:25:49,136
Still no sign.

356
00:25:49,220 --> 00:25:51,389
<i>He's 15 minutes late.</i>

357
00:25:51,472 --> 00:25:53,140
<i>Any chance he made you?</i>

358
00:25:53,224 --> 00:25:54,892
We're pretty hidden up here.

359
00:26:01,732 --> 00:26:03,901
Any chance she made you
and warned him?

360
00:26:03,984 --> 00:26:05,778
<i>I don't see how.</i>

361
00:26:05,861 --> 00:26:07,238
<i>We've been on her since
she got out of the taxi.</i>

362
00:26:07,321 --> 00:26:08,906
Hasn't even looked up
in our direction.

363
00:26:09,699 --> 00:26:10,991
Stand by.

364
00:26:11,075 --> 00:26:12,535
<i>Standing by.</i>

365
00:28:05,606 --> 00:28:07,274
Listen to me.

366
00:28:07,358 --> 00:28:09,318
Another Islamic Emirate
of Afghanistan

367
00:28:09,401 --> 00:28:11,403
will be never won
on the battlefield.

368
00:28:11,487 --> 00:28:15,491
You don't know that.
How can you say that?

369
00:28:15,574 --> 00:28:17,368
The West won't allow it,

370
00:28:17,451 --> 00:28:20,454
no matter what the I.S.I.
is telling you.

371
00:28:23,290 --> 00:28:27,127
Then we will outlast them,
Father.

372
00:28:27,211 --> 00:28:28,796
We will outlast them.

373
00:28:31,799 --> 00:28:33,801
No.

374
00:28:35,594 --> 00:28:38,639
No.

375
00:28:38,722 --> 00:28:41,517
We are just strong enough

376
00:28:41,600 --> 00:28:43,811
never to lose

377
00:28:43,894 --> 00:28:46,897
and just weak enough
never to win.

378
00:28:53,445 --> 00:28:55,573
So you've decided.

379
00:29:00,202 --> 00:29:03,539
What choice do I have
but to accept your decision?

380
00:29:10,254 --> 00:29:14,508
You could do it
as a good soldier...

381
00:29:14,592 --> 00:29:17,428
and a good son.

382
00:29:17,511 --> 00:29:19,930
At the end of a rope?

383
00:29:20,014 --> 00:29:23,267
With a gun to my head?

384
00:29:58,218 --> 00:30:00,429
What do you say now, Jalala?

385
00:30:02,306 --> 00:30:03,641
Will you join me
on this new path?

386
00:30:11,398 --> 00:30:12,858
I will try...

387
00:30:12,941 --> 00:30:16,195
Father...

388
00:30:16,278 --> 00:30:17,655
for you.

389
00:33:19,628 --> 00:33:21,630
Come.

390
00:33:21,713 --> 00:33:24,383
We have much to discuss.

391
00:33:32,432 --> 00:33:34,017
Another ten minutes,
and I'm calling it.

392
00:33:34,101 --> 00:33:35,018
<i>Copy that.</i>

393
00:33:37,145 --> 00:33:39,815
Well?

394
00:33:39,898 --> 00:33:41,024
I don't buy it.

395
00:33:41,108 --> 00:33:42,651
Why make the whole thing up?

396
00:33:42,734 --> 00:33:44,319
Because she didn't want
to go back to Germany.

397
00:33:44,403 --> 00:33:45,696
Look at her.

398
00:33:45,779 --> 00:33:47,197
She's just as bummed
he didn't show as we are.

399
00:33:47,281 --> 00:33:49,408
It's an act.

400
00:33:49,491 --> 00:33:51,076
She must know
we're watching her,

401
00:33:51,159 --> 00:33:51,869
or at least suspect.

402
00:33:51,952 --> 00:33:55,372
That doesn't make her
a liar.

403
00:33:55,455 --> 00:33:57,207
She reported the contact,
didn't she?

404
00:33:57,958 --> 00:33:59,960
What the hell?

405
00:34:00,043 --> 00:34:01,753
Mike, look.

406
00:34:11,138 --> 00:34:12,806
Right on cue.

407
00:34:12,890 --> 00:34:14,141
You knew?

408
00:34:14,224 --> 00:34:16,393
The minute I read
the time and place.

409
00:34:16,476 --> 00:34:18,896
Your people,
do they know?

410
00:34:18,979 --> 00:34:19,938
They do now.

411
00:34:20,022 --> 00:34:21,899
Are you getting this?

412
00:34:21,982 --> 00:34:23,525
I can't make out
a word they're saying.

413
00:34:23,609 --> 00:34:25,402
Negative, problem is we're
aimed right at a wall of sound.

414
00:34:25,485 --> 00:34:28,071
- Fix it.
- We're trying.

415
00:34:30,782 --> 00:34:32,006
Where are we going?

416
00:34:32,089 --> 00:34:33,841
We'll talk by the fountain.

417
00:34:33,925 --> 00:34:36,844
I want to make double sure
they can't hear us.

418
00:34:38,846 --> 00:34:40,056
What's so amusing?

419
00:34:40,139 --> 00:34:43,392
Just admiring the tradecraft.

420
00:34:51,609 --> 00:34:53,611
What do you want?

421
00:34:53,694 --> 00:34:56,822
Come on, admit it... you're
a little pleased to see me.

422
00:34:56,906 --> 00:34:59,367
You know, "pleased" isn't the
first word that comes to mind.

423
00:34:59,450 --> 00:35:02,411
Okay, look, I'm sorry.

424
00:35:02,495 --> 00:35:04,622
Apology is in order.

425
00:35:04,705 --> 00:35:06,666
I didn't mean to leave
your life like that.

426
00:35:06,749 --> 00:35:08,793
Well, it was crowded.

427
00:35:08,876 --> 00:35:09,585
I assumed you didn't want
to be seen.

428
00:35:09,669 --> 00:35:13,798
No, not... not at the bar.
In Moscow.

429
00:35:13,881 --> 00:35:16,676
At the asylum.

430
00:35:16,759 --> 00:35:20,137
I'm sorry I left you alone
in that place.

431
00:35:21,806 --> 00:35:24,767
So... so what was
Samira Noori, then... penance?

432
00:35:24,850 --> 00:35:26,644
Yeah, sort of.

433
00:35:26,727 --> 00:35:28,562
And Roshan Shadman?

434
00:35:28,646 --> 00:35:29,730
Who's that?

435
00:35:29,814 --> 00:35:31,440
Tied to a truck

436
00:35:31,524 --> 00:35:33,818
and dragged through the streets
of Ghazni to his death?

437
00:35:33,901 --> 00:35:35,987
Sorry, I don't know
who that is.

438
00:35:36,070 --> 00:35:39,699
Tell that to his widow,
to his 12-year-old child.

439
00:35:39,782 --> 00:35:41,784
I can see you're angry, but
I had nothing to do with that.

440
00:35:41,867 --> 00:35:45,496
Well, forgive me,
but you're full of shit.

441
00:35:45,579 --> 00:35:48,499
Don't think I don't know
what you're really doing.

442
00:35:48,582 --> 00:35:49,583
You're wrong.

443
00:35:49,667 --> 00:35:52,169
I really was trying to just...

444
00:35:52,253 --> 00:35:55,423
just pick up
where we left off.

445
00:35:55,506 --> 00:35:57,591
Right, whatever that means.

446
00:35:57,675 --> 00:36:00,803
You really do not remember?

447
00:36:04,181 --> 00:36:05,933
Remember what?

448
00:36:08,978 --> 00:36:11,188
Remember what?

449
00:36:11,272 --> 00:36:14,358
I saved your life...

450
00:36:14,442 --> 00:36:16,402
for one thing.

451
00:36:20,031 --> 00:36:22,575
You were trying
to hang yourself

452
00:36:22,658 --> 00:36:26,037
with a rope
made from your bedsheets.

453
00:36:29,749 --> 00:36:34,086
I hadn't seen you in months,
I got there, and by pure luck...

454
00:36:34,170 --> 00:36:35,421
<i>If I was there a minute later,
just a minute later,</i>

455
00:36:35,504 --> 00:36:38,299
you would have been gone.

456
00:36:40,051 --> 00:36:41,677
And after that,
I managed to get you

457
00:36:41,761 --> 00:36:43,929
back on your meds
for a couple weeks.

458
00:36:46,015 --> 00:36:49,643
There was a birch forest
right near the hospital.

459
00:36:49,727 --> 00:36:51,270
<i>You really liked
walking there.</i>

460
00:36:55,566 --> 00:36:57,026
It's true.

461
00:36:57,109 --> 00:37:00,404
Turns out we had
a lot to talk about.

462
00:37:00,488 --> 00:37:02,740
Really?
Like what?

463
00:37:02,823 --> 00:37:04,658
Like your relationship
with Nicholas Brody.

464
00:37:04,742 --> 00:37:07,453
Tell me something you didn't
just read in my file.

465
00:37:09,872 --> 00:37:11,415
You had a daughter with him.

466
00:37:11,499 --> 00:37:14,585
Franny.

467
00:37:14,668 --> 00:37:18,672
You slipped her head underwater

468
00:37:18,756 --> 00:37:20,091
in the bath.

469
00:37:24,011 --> 00:37:27,598
There was a moment
when you actually considered

470
00:37:27,681 --> 00:37:30,434
drowning your own child.

471
00:37:41,654 --> 00:37:42,780
Shh.

472
00:37:46,200 --> 00:37:48,119
And now they aren't
saying a word.

473
00:37:48,202 --> 00:37:49,453
Fuck.

474
00:37:58,254 --> 00:37:59,588
I have to go.

475
00:38:08,139 --> 00:38:09,348
How much of what they did say

476
00:38:09,432 --> 00:38:10,057
are we gonna be able
to recover?

477
00:38:10,141 --> 00:38:10,975
<i>I'm not sure.</i>

478
00:38:11,058 --> 00:38:12,810
<i>I'll get the techs
working on it</i>

479
00:38:12,893 --> 00:38:14,353
<i>once we're back
at the station.</i>

480
00:38:14,437 --> 00:38:15,646
Make it a first priority.

481
00:38:23,571 --> 00:38:26,157
- David.
- Mr. President.

482
00:38:26,240 --> 00:38:27,825
We may have caught a break.

483
00:38:27,908 --> 00:38:30,327
Haqqani released Saul
a little over an hour ago.

484
00:38:30,411 --> 00:38:32,580
What happened?

485
00:38:32,663 --> 00:38:35,624
It turns out Haqqani's son
was an I.S.I. asset.

486
00:38:35,708 --> 00:38:37,918
They promised him
keys to the kingdom.

487
00:38:38,002 --> 00:38:39,670
If he killed Daddy?

488
00:38:39,753 --> 00:38:42,381
Something like that.

489
00:38:42,465 --> 00:38:44,300
Does this mean Daddy
might be willing

490
00:38:44,383 --> 00:38:45,509
to negotiate after all?

491
00:38:45,593 --> 00:38:47,011
Looks that way.

492
00:38:47,094 --> 00:38:49,597
I need you to talk Saul
through some

493
00:38:49,680 --> 00:38:52,349
of the stickier points
of the deal just in case.

494
00:38:52,433 --> 00:38:53,767
He's got to know
where he can compromise,

495
00:38:53,851 --> 00:38:57,813
where to hold the line.

496
00:38:57,897 --> 00:38:59,565
He's expecting your call.

497
00:39:03,235 --> 00:39:04,528
What is it, David?

498
00:39:06,697 --> 00:39:08,991
Last night I asked
the vice president

499
00:39:09,074 --> 00:39:11,827
about an unscheduled trip
to Columbus.

500
00:39:11,911 --> 00:39:14,288
He said he was there
for a football game

501
00:39:14,371 --> 00:39:15,706
with Frank Gillette.

502
00:39:15,789 --> 00:39:17,750
So?

503
00:39:17,833 --> 00:39:19,877
So he neglected to mention
that every other major donor

504
00:39:19,960 --> 00:39:21,921
in the country
was also there.

505
00:39:22,004 --> 00:39:24,840
It was a who's who
of heavy hitters.

506
00:39:24,924 --> 00:39:27,218
He's fundraising for his side.

507
00:39:27,301 --> 00:39:29,178
Not much we can do about that.

508
00:39:29,261 --> 00:39:32,181
Or positioning himself.

509
00:39:32,264 --> 00:39:34,767
Positioning himself?

510
00:39:34,850 --> 00:39:35,935
Well, you're aware Ohio voters
approved a proposition

511
00:39:36,018 --> 00:39:38,729
to move up the state's primary.

512
00:39:38,812 --> 00:39:42,255
They're now number two in line
after the Iowa caucuses.

513
00:39:42,338 --> 00:39:44,560
No vice president
has ever challenged

514
00:39:44,643 --> 00:39:46,747
a sitting president, David.

515
